`ctx-run <dir> "<task>"` is the one-command billed cage entry point: it
runs a caged agent session via `ctx_cage::lifecycle::execute`, then
optionally refreshes context summaries. Agent auth for the cage itself is
the operator's Claude Code subscription — this binary configures nothing
for that; the optional `~/.config/ctx/env` file only feeds the
post-run `ctx-scan --update` child (`CTX_AGENT_CMD` + `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`),
never the cage or shell. Typing `ctx-run` is treated as the spend
authorization, so there's no `--allow-spend` flag here (contrast with
other cage entry points that may require one).

`load_env_file` requires the env file be `0600` when present (rejects any
group/other bits) since it holds an API key; missing file is fine, returns
empty map. `parse_env` does simple `KEY=VALUE` line parsing with `#`
comments and quote-stripping — not a real dotenv parser (no escaping,
multiline, or export handling).

`confirm_summarize` only prompts when stdin `is_terminal()` — piped/CI
runs silently skip summarization (same discipline as the PTY relay in
ADR-048). `refresh_summaries` runs `ctx-scan <dir> --update` and never
fails the overall run on refresh failure; it prints a manual-recovery
hint (`ctx-scan <dir> --update --approve`) to stderr instead — the
session's deliverable already landed, so a refresh problem is
maintenance, not failure.

`warn_if_no_hooks` checks for `.claude/settings.json` in the target and
warns (doesn't fail) if absent, since the context-chain hook requires it.

Sibling binaries (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan`) are resolved
from `current_exe`'s directory, overridable via `CTX_VERIFY_BIN`,
`CTX_CONTEXT_BIN`, `CTX_SCAN_BIN` — same resolution convention as
`ctx-cage`.